I had such a lovely weekend I just wanted to write it down. <!-- more --> I told my boyfriend on Wednesday that I wanted to take him on a date Friday night - we planned for a dinner at one of our fav vegan restaurants and then seeing Free Solo afterwards. Friday night rolls around and he and I both were feeling pretty run down after the week we had, so we stayed in. I ended up coming over with a bottle of wine already wearing my pajamas with my heating pad in tow for the neck pain he was having. We cuddled up on the couch and he ordered us vegetable fried rice and we watched Moon on Netflix. Such a simple evening but it was so so nice and cozy with the rain and chill outside and the warmth and love inside. (Was that? like?way too cheesy? lol) I woke up before him and got my stuff around to go home and go on a run because I skipped it Friday night. Easy 3.5 miles in the rain and wind on super tired muscles. One of those runs that youâ€™re immediately over before it even starts - I just needed 35 minutes on my feet and I got it, but I did not enjoy it! lol But sometimes thatâ€™s how it goes. Run and done. Ate yummy breakfast with hot delicious coffee & showered. Then I got all nice to go out with my boyfriend! I donâ€™t wear makeup to work so getting ready to go out on the weekends is always a treat for me to spend some extra time on myself. I drove my boyfriend and I to the pot store up the street and we each got some CBD oil. (Finally got some of my own, I was just using his every now and then but Iâ€™m glad Iâ€™ve got my own now!) Then we went to the camera store downtown where we bought film for our cameras! We got three rolls each. He checked out some more equipment then we were off to the restaurant for dinner. We got there right at five when they opened for dinner and we were the only ones in there for maybe ten minutes then it filled up pretty quickly and we were surrounded by other couples and families. We ordered an appetizer and it was SO delicious! It was some kind of red lentil pecan pate and oh my goodness!! Then we got our dinners - he got a Mexican-inspired dish and I got a portobello wellington plate and we were both pleased as punch. I was so full but when the waitress brought the dessert menu we couldnâ€™t help but look?and then ordered the plum quince crisp with vegan vanilla ice cream. So. Good. We left the restaurant and tried to make our movie, but it was sold out when we got there! We were both a bit disappointed but we arranged to see it another time this week. I drove us back to my apartment and we fed Joe and hung out with him for a bit, gave him lots of scratches and pets, then grabbed another bottle of wine and some frozen waffles for the morning and went back to his place. (Heâ€™s allergic to cats. *cue tears* lol) We got into our jammies and while he watched the last two episodes of House of Cards I played with my camera and worked on my embroidery and repaired a button on his duvet cover for him. I took two photos of him on my new camera (my first photos ever on the camera!) and then after he was done watching his episodes we finished Moon. We were in such goofy moods because of the wine and funny conversations weâ€™d had throughout the day, I was having so much fun. I took my make up off, brushed my teeth and hopped into bed where we were happy to know weâ€™d get an extra hour of sleep because of daylight savings. We woke up and cuddled for a bit before rolling out of bed to make breakfast. He made us coffee (in the Chemex I bought him for his birthday, he loves it!) and then he made us waffles. We ate on the couch watching the office :) a great Sunday morning. I asked him if he still wanted to go downtown to see about this wood slab sale. We got dressed and headed out. I brought my camera just in case. Before we went home he asked if I wanted to go to the farmerâ€™s market. Iâ€™m a red-blooded American girl so of course I said yes. We saw? SO MANY DOGS!!!! Some notable ones: 2 Westies, what looked like a miniature golden retriever wearing a blue bandana sleeping at the feet of his owner friend while he read a book and drank coffee outside, a fucking ginormous white dog that I can only describe as looking like Falkor from the Neverending Story named Yukon who was only 5 YEARS OLD but weighed 175lbs (so beautiful and I got to pet him and talk to his owner friend who was worried I would get my sweater furry by petting him and I was just like sir you donâ€™t know me lol), a HUGE black dog that was probably Yukonâ€™s friend, a golden retriever puppy who decided to lay down in the middle of the market because he was tired, a shaggy doggo sitting in a pile of leaves and then freaking out when he discovered a new leaf next to him, 3 huge german shepherds, 2 backpack dogs, one dog that was totally a human in another life that had similar-looking owner friends, a cocker-spaniel kind of dog whose owner friend let me take a photo of her and also give her a treat (her name was Maddy), an ancient golden retriever, an australian shepherd with his head in his owner friendâ€™s lap because he was so pooped, and finally every other dog I saw because theyâ€™re all important. I drove back to my apartment and realized how great the lighting was by the lake - I pulled over and took a couple of photos of the fall trees and the colors they offered. Delirium Inspired by the moments of deep dreams where the space enters abtraccion mode or basic graphics in which we are panic state to have no control of the suffering of the material transformation and culminates in contemplating movement of the entities Onirism or dream delirium Onirism is usually characterized by visual hallucinations, but may also be accompanied by those that involve the sense of touch and very rarely also includes auditory hallucinations. There are more complex combinations of onirism formed by hallucinations that involve several senses, which are called with the term â€œdream delirium? Applied to Art It is worth mentioning that the term onirism can be seen and analyzed from an artistic perspective. In this way it can even be considered as a process of abstraction and synthesis, in which the artist is stimulated by reality, which he internalizes by choosing (arbitrarily or heuristically) certain details or events external to him or her, which he studies, remember, in some way he ponders or treasures them and finally reflects them in his work to share them with others. So we have that the artist uses and is used to interpret his dream or dream hallucinations, allusions, similes, metaphors, signs, and symbols. In specific cases: when words are used, then it is Literary Onirism; when images are used then it is Pictorial Onirism; when tangible forms (sculpture, jewelry, dance, ballet) are used, it is Plastic Onirism.
